			<h2 class="comments-title">
			7 thoughts on &ldquo;<span>The re-writing of history:  The misuse of the draft “dodger” myth against  Iraq war resisters in Canada</span>&rdquo;		</h2>

		<ol class="commentlist">
				<li class="pingback even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-36233">
		<p>Pingback: <a href='http://activehistory.ca/2012/10/new-paper-the-re-writing-of-history-the-misuse-of-the-draft-dodger/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>The re-writing of history: The misuse of the draft “dodger” myth against Iraq war resisters in Canada</a> </p>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-43966">
		<article id="comment-43966" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ca2988285fbd691b83780f79bafd3924?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ca2988285fbd691b83780f79bafd3924?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://warwalksforhealth.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>warbirdie</a></b> </cite><a href="http://activehistory.ca/papers/history-papers-12/#comment-43966"><time datetime="2013-04-01T05:04:42+00:00">April 1, 2013 at 5:04 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>I am sorry, but your argument that she is some sort of victim is completely without merit. She DID volunteer&#8230; and she DID take the money and then she just didn&#8217;t like the job, so instead of being an adult and sticking it out, she made a run for the border. Not only should she have been deported, she should have been horsewhipped out of the country. </p>
<p>I don&#8217;t have much respect for draft dodgers, but I do respect that they didn&#8217;t have a choice about going to war. For them, there wasn&#8217;t an option of doing some form of civil service instead. You cannot equate a military deserter with a draftee.</p>
<p>Mrs. Rivera HAD a choice. She joined the army for financial reasons. I will fully admit that the US military functions in some ways as a second welfare system, but that doesn&#8217;t change the simple fact that she made the choice to join up. You can call it buyers remorse, but it doesn&#8217;T make her  a victim. </p>
<p>Had Mrs. Rivera been a responsible  adult, she would have served out her contract and left the military. I know plenty of former US soldiers who did just that- many of whom didn&#8217;t support the war. Why is she special? Why does she deserve special treatment? Desertion is against american law. You don&#8217;t have agree with it, but it isn&#8217;t as if Mrs. Rivera had no idea that if she deserted and was caught there would be consequences. She DESERVES a dishonourable discharge. </p>
<p>Why do you believe she shouldn&#8217;t be held accountable for her actions? Because it was war? One cannot even use the argument here that she joined before there was a war, and then a war she didn&#8217;t agree with started and so she left. When she joined, the war had been going on for five years.</p>
<p>If you don&#8217;t want to be a soldier, don&#8217;t put on the uniform. If you take the &#8216;King&#8217;s Shilling&#8217; then suck it up.</p>
<p>To be perfectly honest, I think that calling her a conscientious objector insults every person who suffered under that label in history.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-44043">
