	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-44176">
		<article id="comment-44176" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f4009a745b0e9ad0770b9bc6c9741005?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f4009a745b0e9ad0770b9bc6c9741005?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">Name Here</b> </cite><a href="http://activehistory.ca/papers/history-papers-12/#comment-44176"><time datetime="2013-05-25T03:45:35+00:00">May 25, 2013 at 3:45 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>I suppose Iraqi civilians should also &#8220;suck it up&#8221;, after all there is a &#8220;job&#8221; to do.  Without those standing up for personal convictions, this world stands to repeat past mistakes in the following of a naturally fallibly human chain of command.  To argue that one has made a legal commitment (or worse a financial commitment by taking the &#8220;king&#8217;s shilling&#8221;) to a government which outweighs all conceivable scenarios, attempts to simplify the problem by separating humanity from the equation.  A great many progressions in the human race have been in the attempt to keep a complex problem &#8220;simple&#8221; with constructs later determined to be incomplete.</p>
<p>Regardless of the apparent obligation, do you really want soldiers who aren&#8217;t fully committed to their task for one reason or another?  Whether this thinking comes before, or during an enlistment, the risks are the same in a combat role.  Let us at least ensure soldiers are fully committed and willing.</p>
<p>Anyway, the whole argument from warbirdie again overlooks (simplifies) the (obvious) point, that there is apparently an effort to shift the outward facing values of the country, arguably without the support of the majority of people in the country itself.  But I suppose with a shut up and don&#8217;t ask questions mentality that might be ok, for some.</p>
<p>This article deserves more comments.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="pingback even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-52520">
		<p>Pingback: <a href='http://pamelamariestewart.com/2014/11/26/dear-enemies-happy-thanksgiving/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Dear Enemies: Happy Thanksgiving! | Pamela Stewart &#8211; Freelance Writer</a> </p>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-56573">
		<article id="comment-56573" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/a2435eeb914a3f1fef365ec2cc9d6bbf?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/a2435eeb914a3f1fef365ec2cc9d6bbf?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">W.A. Cook</b> </cite><a href="http://activehistory.ca/papers/history-papers-12/#comment-56573"><time datetime="2015-01-11T11:29:43+00:00">January 11, 2015 at 11:29 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Washington State U.S.A.<br />
August 9, 2010</p>
<p>The Right Honorable Stephen Harper,<br />
Prime Minister of Canada<br />
24 Sussex Drive at Rideau Gate<br />
Ottawa, Ontario K1A 0A3<br />
Canada </p>
<p>Subject: Recognition of American Vietnam War era draftees</p>
<p>Prime Minister Harper:</p>
<p>As Prime Minster, you must understand the inherent obligations citizens have to their country. During the United States involvement in the Vietnam War, Canada offered  sanctuary to nearly 50,000 United States men, of military draft age, who refused to honor their moral and legal obligation to their country. Our President, Jimmy Carter, pardoned those men on January 21, 1977 for “…violations of the Military Selective Service Act…” if their actions did not “… involve force or violence”. Many returned to their former country after the pardon.  </p>
<p>In my opinion, the American men who fled to your country, to avoid the Vietnam War era draft, should have applied for conscientious objector status.  However I suspect that few would have qualified. We draftees did what our country expected and needed during a time of war but we have not received any recognition for that service to America. However draft dodgers continue to make the news: It was reported that Castlegar, B.C, in July of 2006, hosted a “Vietnam War Draft-Dodgers Reunion”.  Also at least one United States veteran’s group view Vietnam War draft dodgers as anti-war heroes so draftees have been forgotten. </p>
<p>Vietnam War draftees, which include men who filled draft dodgers slots, had the moral courage, not shown by the draft dodgers, to serve their country. So I ask you to help in getting some type of formal recognition for the American men who did no need to be pardoned nor did they expect Canada to protect them from their government. </p>
<p>Your laws made it possible for young American men to avoid their moral and legal obligations to their country.  So it is seems reasonable to ask you for help in honoring the American men who did not use the Canadian government as an aide. My recommendation for an American Conscription Ribbon is enclosed.  </p>
<p>Sincerely,</p>
<p>William Anthony Cook, American Vietnam War Draftee 1965 – Vietnam 1966/67</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

